==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: omega
<hw>o*me"ga</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧*m⟦emac⟧"g⟦adot⟧ <it>or</it>
⟦omac⟧*m⟦amac⟧"g⟦adot⟧ <it>or</it> ⟦omac⟧"m⟦esl⟧*g⟦adot⟧; 277)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <grk>'w^ me`ga</grk>, i.e., the great
or long o. Cf. <er>Mickle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The last letter
of the Greek alphabet. See <er>Alpha</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The last; the end; hence, death.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧<qex>Omega</qex>! thou art Lord,⟦rdquo⟧ they said.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Alpha and Omega</b></col>, <cd>the beginning and the
ending; hence, the chief, the whole.</cd> <rj><au>Rev. i.
8.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The alpha and <qex>omega</qex> of science.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Herschel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Omegoid</ent>⟦br⟧
